  "takeaways": [
    "This is the first-pass liability-incidence audit for the TOC/ROW block. It treats the bundle as economically real and asks whether each leg behaves like an in-scope bank-deposit component rather than only like broad support.",
    "The goal here is not to relitigate arithmetic. It is to test strict deposit incidence by leg using the already-built TOC, ROW, and path-split evidence.",
    "TOC continues to look like real Treasury cash plumbing in raw quarterly data: contemporaneous TGA-vs-TOC corr \u2248 0.95.",
    "But TOC does not yet earn strict-component status: at h0 the in-scope deposit proxy captures only about 0.39 of TOC while reserves capture about 1.26.",
    "ROW looks weaker as an in-scope deposit leg and stronger as broader external support: checkable-ROW-bank corr \u2248 0.02, foreign-NONTS corr \u2248 -0.17.",
    "The h0 ROW split points the same way: in-scope deposit proxy share \u2248 0.02, external-support share \u2248 2.26.",
    "The combined support bundle remains the dominant treatment-side issue: h0 TOC/ROW support bundle \u2248 65.40, with TOC signed contribution \u2248 70.44, ROW signed contribution \u2248 11.76, while the remaining core residual is only \u2248 -5.51.",
    "The existing path split still matters for interpretation: quarterly preferred bundle path = `direct_deposit_path_dominant`, but the bundle is not yet validated as a strict bank-deposit component."
  ]
